We will use a function to clean the column name:
```julia
function clean_column(col::AbstractString)
    return lowercase(replace(rstrip(lstrip(col)), r"\s|-" => "_"))
end
```
This function takes an `AbstractString` type argument for generality and uses the Julia standard library methods `lowercase`, `replace`, `rstrip`, `lstrip` to perform the cleaning.

The `replace` function replaces all occurrences of whitespaces and hyphens with underscores using regular expressions. The `rstrip` and `lstrip` functions remove any leading or trailing whitespaces. Finally, the `lowercase` function converts the column name to lowercase.

To test this function, we can create a simple unit test:
```julia
@testset "Cleaning Column" begin
    @test clean_column("My Column") == "my_column"
    @test clean_column(" MY COLUMN  ") == "my_column"
end
```
This ensures that the function works correctly and handles both lowercase and uppercase column names.
